The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Sports | In the City
                                                                                                               IN THE CITY
                  
	 Anand Mehta, seven-time national bridge champion and Sachin Tendulkars father-in-law, will be among the 700 players in the fray for the Golden Jubilee Bridge Championships to be held at Khudiram Anushilan Kendra from Thursday to Sunday.      
	The championship would be held for pairs as well as team events. Arun Bapat, Sunil Macher, Anil Padhye and Raju Tolani (all from Mumbai), K. Murthy and R. Krishnan (both from Chennai) and Ashok Goel (Delhi) are the other top players who would be vying for honours.      
	Briefing the media on Tuesday, West Bengal Bridge Association secretary Arijit Guha said the Calcutta Bridge Club will also felicitate Mehta and other greats like Robi Roy, S.R. Ghosh, Santanu Ghosh and Samir Kumar Ghosh (Gorada) during the championship.          
	 Timir Ghosh of Murshidabad was unanimously elected vice-president of the Cricket Association of Bengal on Tuesday after Rathin Sarkar of South 24-Parganas withdrew his name on Monday. Ghosh is also the chairman of the CABs coaches sub-committee and a member of the district committee.      
	Jagmohan Dalmiya, CAB president, said that another special general body meeting would be held within the next few weeks.          
	 Ballygunge United scored 216 against Tapan Memorial in a CAB league match on Tuesday. Diptendu Mahata top scored with 52. In reply, Tapan Memorial were 35 without loss at the close of play.       
